[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":989},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnuxt\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F22\u002Fnuxt-2x-handbook-02-architecture-overview\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnuxt\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F22\u002Fnuxt-2x-handbook-02-architecture-overview\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnuxt\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F22\u002Fnuxt-2x-handbook-02-architecture-overview\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnuxt\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F22\u002Fnuxt-2x-handbook-02-architecture-overview\u002F":965,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnuxt\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F22\u002Fnuxt-2x-handbook-02-architecture-overview\u002F":974},"\u002Fnuxt\u002F20211022\u002F3508219327\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":949,"date":950,"description":19,"extension":951,"lang":952,"meta":953,"navigation":369,"path":954,"readingMinutes":955,"seo":956,"standalone":957,"stem":958,"tags":959,"tldr":962,"updated":950,"url":963,"__hash__":964},"content\u002Fen\u002FNuxt\u002Fnuxt-2x-handbook-02-architecture-overview.md","Nuxt.js 2.x Hands-On Handbook (2) — Architecture Overview","8130329572",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":936},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,30,40,49,52,62,65,72,76,79,86,89,97,104,108,113,116,136,139,157,177,257,271,278,284,305,420,429,432,450,545,556,561,568,655,664,676,723,770,780,784,797,902,909,912,915,918,923,927,932],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Last chapter we got the basic Nuxt.js example environment ready. Now let's walk through the overall Nuxt.js architecture.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"nuxtjs","Nuxt.js",[17,25,26],{},"Nuxt.js is basically a bundle of frameworks — Node.js, Vue.js, Webpack, Babel.js, and so on. You can think of it as Vue CLI on steroids, with a Node.js environment thrown in.",[17,28,29],{},"Nuxt.js has two modes:",[31,32,33,37],"ul",{},[34,35,36],"li",{},"Server Side Render (SSR)",[34,38,39],{},"Static Site Generation (SSG)",[17,41,42,43,48],{},"(See ",[44,45,47],"a",{"href":46},"\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2021\u002F05\u002F29\u002Fspa-csr-ssr-mpa-ssg-explained\u002F","SPA, CSR, SSR, MPA, SSG — A Quick Take on Frontend Terminology"," for more.)",[17,50,51],{},"So why use Nuxt.js? And why's it so popular? Is SSR only doable in Nuxt.js? Can't you do it in Vue CLI?",[17,53,54,55,61],{},"Honestly, Vue CLI can do SSR — but you need a package called ",[44,56,60],{"href":57,"rel":58},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.npmjs.com\u002Fpackage\u002Fvue-server-renderer",[59],"nofollow","vue-server-renderer"," and you have to write Express in Node.js. You'd need solid Node.js chops or you're in WTF territory.",[17,63,64],{},"So rolling your own SSR is painful, and Nuxt.js solves that for you. You don't need to be a Node.js expert to spin up an SSR or PWA setup, and you can even use Nuxt.js as a backend (like Express.js).",[17,66,67,68,71],{},"I'll save the details of rolling your own SSR with ",[44,69,60],{"href":57,"rel":70},[59]," for another time — for now, just understand why Nuxt.js exists.",[12,73,75],{"id":74},"project-structure","Project structure",[17,77,78],{},"Last chapter we got the basic Nuxt.js environment ready.",[17,80,81],{},[82,83],"img",{"alt":84,"src":85},"Architecture","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNuxtjs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-10-22%2021.37.00.png",[17,87,88],{},"Each folder has its own purpose. Before diving in, one piece of advice:",[17,90,91,92,96],{},"\"Let go of some Vue CLI habits — especially manual ",[93,94,95],"code",{},"vue-router"," setup.\"",[17,98,99,100,103],{},"Why? Because Nuxt.js auto-generates ",[93,101,102],{},"router.js"," — you don't write it at all. Let me walk through the folders.",[105,106,107],"h3",{"id":107},"assets",[17,109,110,112],{},[93,111,107],{}," is basically your asset library. You'll typically see SCSS and images here — files that go through compilation. Same concept as Vue CLI.",[105,114,115],{"id":115},"components",[17,117,118,120,121,124,125,124,128,131,132,135],{},[93,119,115],{}," should be familiar — where you put your components, like ",[93,122,123],{},"Modal.vue",", ",[93,126,127],{},"Navbar.vue",[93,129,130],{},"Footer.vue",". These are usually ",[93,133,134],{},"import","-ed in like in Vue CLI, so I won't dwell on it.",[105,137,138],{"id":138},"layouts",[17,140,141,143,144,147,148,150,151,153,154,156],{},[93,142,138],{}," is a bit special. In a Vue CLI setup, your outer layer is ",[93,145,146],{},"App.vue"," and you nest things downward — usually wiring up ",[93,149,127],{}," and ",[93,152,130],{}," there for shared layout. But Nuxt.js doesn't have ",[93,155,146],{}," at all. So what do you do?",[17,158,159,160,163,164,167,168,170,171,173,174,176],{},"Don't worry — Nuxt.js gives you a way. Just create a ",[93,161,162],{},"default.vue"," inside ",[93,165,166],{},"layouts\u002F",", and it works like ",[93,169,146],{},". Try creating a ",[93,172,162],{}," in ",[93,175,166],{}," with:",[178,179,184],"pre",{"className":180,"code":181,"language":182,"meta":183,"style":183},"language-vue shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","\u003Ctemplate>\n  \u003Cdiv>\n    This is header\n    \u003Cnuxt \u002F>\n    This is footer\n  \u003C\u002Fdiv>\n\u003C\u002Ftemplate>\n","vue","",[93,185,186,202,213,219,231,237,247],{"__ignoreMap":183},[187,188,191,195,199],"span",{"class":189,"line":190},"line",1,[187,192,194],{"class":193},"s8XSl","\u003C",[187,196,198],{"class":197},"syv7_","template",[187,200,201],{"class":193},">\n",[187,203,205,208,211],{"class":189,"line":204},2,[187,206,207],{"class":193},"  \u003C",[187,209,210],{"class":197},"div",[187,212,201],{"class":193},[187,214,216],{"class":189,"line":215},3,[187,217,218],{"class":193},"    This is header\n",[187,220,222,225,228],{"class":189,"line":221},4,[187,223,224],{"class":193},"    \u003C",[187,226,227],{"class":197},"nuxt",[187,229,230],{"class":193}," \u002F>\n",[187,232,234],{"class":189,"line":233},5,[187,235,236],{"class":193},"    This is footer\n",[187,238,240,243,245],{"class":18